## What Each Source Captures

### Azure Firewall DNS Proxy
The firewall acts as a middleman for DNS queries. When any device or system inside the
Azure network needs to resolve a public internet domain — google.com, a software update
server, or a malicious C2 domain — that query passes through the firewall. The firewall
logs every query and every response before forwarding it on.

**What this means for coverage:**
Any Azure VNet resource configured to use the firewall as its DNS server will appear in
these logs. This is the broadest DNS visibility available in this environment.

**What this means for security:**
This is the primary detection surface. Threats like malware beaconing, DNS tunneling,
data exfiltration over DNS, and connections to known malicious domains will show up here.

### Azure Private DNS Resolver
A Microsoft-managed service running inside Azure whose job is to resolve internal private
names — resources that do not exist on the public internet. When an Azure VM needs to reach
a private database, a private storage account, or another internal service, it queries the
resolver to get the internal IP address. This is essentially the internal phone book for
Azure resources communicating with each other.

**What this means for coverage:**
Internal Azure-to-Azure traffic and hybrid on-premises to Azure name resolution.
Lower volume than the firewall proxy because it only handles internal queries.

**What this means for security:**
Supplementary detection surface. Useful for spotting unusual internal resource lookups,
lateral movement between internal systems, and DNS resolver policy violations.
The `resolverpolicyruleaction` field is particularly useful — it records when a resolver
policy fired and what action was taken, providing an audit trail for internal DNS controls.

