## How DNS Queries Travel — Path Reference

**On-premises device resolving an internal name:**
```
Laptop → Windows DNS Server → knows the answer → responds directly → done
Nothing leaves the building. Only visible in DnsEvents if AMA agent is installed.
```

**On-premises device resolving a public internet name:**
```
Laptop → Windows DNS Server → does not know → forwarder kicks in
→ Azure Firewall DNS Proxy → logs it → forwards to public DNS
→ answer returns through firewall → logged again → back to laptop
Visible in AzureDiagnostics.
```

**Azure VM resolving a public internet name:**
```
Azure VM → Azure Firewall DNS Proxy → logs it → forwards to public DNS
→ answer returns through firewall → logged → back to VM
Visible in AzureDiagnostics.
```

**Azure VM resolving an internal on-premises name:**
```
Azure VM → Azure Firewall DNS Proxy → forwards to Private DNS Resolver
→ Resolver forwards to on-premises Windows DNS Server → answer comes back
→ through Resolver → through Firewall → logged → back to VM
Visible in AzureDiagnostics and DNSQueryLogs.
```

**Azure service resolving another Azure private resource:**
```
Azure Service → Private DNS Resolver → answers from Azure private DNS zones
→ back to service
Visible in DNSQueryLogs only.
```

**Compromised device bypassing DNS entirely (no port 53 controls in place):**
```
Malware → sends query directly to 8.8.8.8 on port 53 → goes straight to internet
→ answer comes back directly
Visible nowhere. No log captures this.
```

**Compromised device attempting bypass (port 53 controls in place):**
```
Malware → tries to send query directly to 8.8.8.8 on port 53
→ firewall intercepts and redirects to DNS proxy → logged
→ or firewall blocks the packet entirely → query fails, malware cannot resolve
Visible in AzureDiagnostics or blocked entirely.
```

